<h2>Solar Panels in Colorado</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Colorado ranks among the top 10 states for solar irradiance, receiving between 4.5 to 6.5 peak sun hours daily depending on location and season. The Front Range cities like Denver, Boulder, and Fort Collins typically see 5.2-5.5 peak sun hours annually, while areas in the San Luis Valley and southeastern plains can exceed 6.0 peak sun hours. This high solar irradiance, combined with the state's elevation advantage, results in exceptional photovoltaic system performance throughout most of the year.</p>

<p>Seasonal variations in Colorado create interesting production patterns, with summer months producing 40-50% more electricity than winter months. However, the state's cold, clear winter days still provide significant solar generation, often exceeding production in cloudier, more temperate climates. Snow can temporarily reduce production, but Colorado's intense sun and steep roof angles typically clear panels quickly. A typical 6kW residential system in Colorado generates between 8,000-9,500 kWh annually, covering 70-90% of average household electricity consumption.</p>

<p>The state's diverse geography means solar potential varies significantly by region. Western Slope communities like Grand Junction enjoy some of the highest solar irradiance in the nation, while mountain communities may experience reduced winter production due to shorter daylight hours and increased snow cover. However, even mountain locations often outperform solar systems in many other states due to increased UV radiation at altitude and reflective snow conditions that can boost panel performance.</p>

