<h2>HVAC Systems in Colorado</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Colorado's semi-arid continental climate presents unique HVAC challenges and opportunities. The state experiences significant temperature swings both seasonally and daily, with summer highs often reaching 85-95¬∞F while winter lows drop to 10-20¬∞F in populated areas. This wide temperature range requires HVAC systems capable of efficient heating and cooling, making heat pumps increasingly popular for their year-round versatility and energy efficiency.</p>

<p>For cooling systems in Colorado, a SEER rating of 14-16 is typically recommended for optimal efficiency without over-investing in capacity rarely needed due to the state's relatively mild summers and low humidity. The dry climate means evaporative cooling systems remain viable and cost-effective in many areas, particularly on the eastern plains and Western Slope. However, traditional central air conditioning is preferred in metro areas where air quality concerns make fresh air intake less desirable during certain periods.</p>

<p>Heating requirements dominate energy consumption in most Colorado locations, with natural gas furnaces historically serving as the primary heating source. However, modern cold-climate heat pumps are gaining popularity due to their efficiency and ability to provide both heating and cooling. Ground-source heat pumps work exceptionally well in Colorado's stable soil temperatures, though installation costs are higher. The state's altitude also affects HVAC performance, with systems needing proper sizing adjustments for reduced air density at elevations above 3,000 feet.</p>

